 <div class="title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Ramsey Growth with Climate Tipping: Only Catastrophic Damages</div>
 <p id="Par10" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Consider a continuous-time Ramsey growth model with a constant population. Fossil fuel 
  <span class="italic">E</span> is input into the production process, has constant marginal cost 
  <span class="italic">d</span> &gt; 0, and (given abundance of coal and shale gas) is in abundant supply. There is a carbon-free imperfect substitute for fossil fuel 
  <span class="italic">R</span>, renewable energy, with constant cost 
  <span class="italic">c</span> &gt; 0. Capital 
  <span class="italic">K</span>, fossil fuel and the renewable substitute are cooperative factors of production. Total factor productivity is 
  <span class="italic">A</span> before the regime shift and drops to 
  <div id="IEq1" class="inline-formula">
   <div class="alternatives">
    <span id="M1" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ (1 - \pi )A &lt; A $$\end{document}</span>
